Here's an example using the jSerialComm library:

```java
import com.fazecast.jSerialComm.*;

public class ReadWriteSerial {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SerialPort port = SerialPort.getCommPort("COM5");
        port.setComPortParameters(9600, 8, 1, 0); // Configure the port settings
        port.openPort(); // Open the serial port

        // Create a separate thread for reading from the serial port
        Thread readThread = new Thread(() -> {
            try {
                byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
                while (true) {
                    int numRead = port.readBytes(buffer, buffer.length);
                    if (numRead > 0) {
                        String receivedData = new String(buffer, 0, numRead);
                        System.out.println("Received: " + receivedData);
                    }
                    Thread.sleep(1);
                }
            } catch (Exception e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
        });
        readThread.start();

        // Send data to the serial port from the main thread
        try {
            String sendData = "Hello from Java!";
            port.writeBytes(sendData.getBytes(), sendData.length());
            System.out.println("Sent: " + sendData);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        // Close the serial port
        port.closePort();
    }
}
```

In this example, we use the jSerialComm library to open the `"COM5"` serial port and configure its parameters. We create a separate thread to continuously read from the port and print the received data. In the main thread, we send data to the port.

Please note that for this code to work, you need to have the jSerialComm library included in your project or build path. You can obtain it from the official website or Maven repository.

